<subSubSection id="D180FF5F6036728D9866DF901D93E2B9" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" type="comments">
<paragraph id="6554412FDCAFFC942556C603CBFB98B5" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="05C573867E67BF941B138528B655A603" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName id="369EA80C4A6B5D026A99C5F03B0ECB4D" authority="Dumort., 1824 (Clarion ex P.Beauv.)" authorityName="Sodiro" authorityYear="1930" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Deyeuxia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Deyeuxia macrostachya" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="macrostachya">
<emphasis id="08316C45127173F94323253D8DDE79CA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Deyeuxia macrostachya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the type specimen collected by Sodiro in 
<normalizedToken id="84D04A0FD4D8278BA87CADC30E511164" originalValue="páramo">paramo</normalizedToken>
grasslands close to mount Pichincha and Chimborazo, Ecuador. We found no noticeable differences between this and Pilgers specimens. The large, lax panicle with semiverticillate branches, similar spikelet morphology including the lemma apex bifid with aristulate teeth and rachilla hairs only reaching the apex of the palea, support 
<taxonomicName id="F1504E8543F6DBEE4F2EA0F1951B621C" genus="D." lsidName="D. macrostachya" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="macrostachya">
<emphasis id="20BCF122C97F7979262EF8F4EEC23987" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">D. macrostachya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being synonymised under 
<taxonomicName id="94215716E8CC5C4F0F5A6AB97ECB1F8C" class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Gramineae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. macrophylla" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="macrophylla">
<emphasis id="9E87E7B8344ACE653D05AC908EB502B8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">C. macrophylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
